'''Matthew Hancock''' (born 2 October 1978) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who was elected as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]] at the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|general election in May 2010]].

==Early life==
Hancock was born in and grew up on a farm in rural [[Cheshire]], in a farming family. Hancock was educated at Farndon County Primary School, in [[Farndon, Cheshire]] and [[The King's School Chester|The King's School]], an [[independent school]] in [[Chester]] in [[Cheshire]].<ref name="bio">[http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Hancock_Matthew.aspx Candidate biography, Conservative homepage]</ref> He gained a first class honours degree in [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] from the [[University of Oxford]], and a Master's Degree in Economics from the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name="bio"/> Hancock has been a member of the Conservative Party since 1999.<ref>http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/matthew-hancock/84378</ref>

==Career==
After university, Hancock briefly worked for his family<U+2019>s computer software company,<ref>http://elections.edelman.co.uk/2010/04/candidate-of-the-day-matthew-hancock-west-suffolk/</ref> before moving to London to work as an economist at the [[Bank of England]], specialising in the housing market.<ref name="Times">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/article696213.ece The Times, 26 March 2006]</ref> In 2005 he became an economic adviser to the Shadow [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[George Osborne]], later becoming Osborne's chief of staff.<ref name="bio"/> As part of this role he managed the Conservative Party's Treasury Team, which advised on policy and commanded a team of 12 advisers. The ''[[Eastern Daily Press]]'' called Hancock "one of the key architects of the Conservative Party's financial plans to get Britain out of recession",<ref>http://www.edp24.co.uk/content/edp24/news/story.aspx?brand=EDPOnline&category=News&tBrand=EDPOnline&tCategory=xDefault&itemid=NOED31%20Jan%202010%2009:32:41:950</ref> and ''[[the Times]]'' named Hancock as one of [[David Cameron]]'s "courtiers", and referred to him as a "working-class northerner".<ref name="Times"/> During this time, Hancock was also Treasurer of the [[Westminster North (UK Parliament constituency)|Westminster North]] Conservatives.<ref>http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2010/01/matt-hancock-george-osbornes-chief-of-staff-selected-for-suffolk-west.html#comment-6a00d83451b31c69e2012877347b62970c</ref>

He stepped down from his role with the party in February 2010 after being selected for the final six potential candidates for the [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk constituency]] in the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|2010 general election]]. Hancock narrowly won the selection contest, which took place in [[Mildenhall, Suffolk|Mildenhall]], after four rounds of voting, beating Natalie Elphicke by 88 votes to 81 votes in the final round of voting.<ref name="NJ">[http://www.newmarketjournal.co.uk/news/Tory-hopeful-Matthew-Hancock-moves.6142543.jp Newmarket Journal, 11 March 2010, accessed 9 May 2010]</ref> [[Sam Gyimah]], who became the Member of Parliament for the [[East Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|East Surrey constituency]], came third in the selection.<ref>http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2010/01/matt-hancock-george-osbornes-chief-of-staff-selected-for-suffolk-west.html</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described Hancock's selection as "a great loss to the Shadow Chancellor, but [Hancock will] provide economic talent for the ministerial benches in the debt struggle ahead".<ref>http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/benedictbrogan/100010394/is-george-osborne-about-to-lose-his-chief-of-staff/</ref>

==Parliament==
Hancock won the West Suffolk seat with 24,312 votes, 13,050 votes ahead of [[Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat]] candidate, Belinda Brooks-Gordon.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/f10.stm 2010 election results, BBC News 7 May 2010]</ref> Hancock made his [[maiden speech]] in a debate about education on 7th June 2010.<ref>http://www.theyworkforyou.com/debate/?id=2010-06-07c.113.0</ref> Hancock describes constituency work as "incredibly satisfying, directly helping people to solve sometimes desperate problems. It's rewarding stuff, and a privilege to use the famous green headed notepaper that can help people who are at the end of their tether. And it puts [[Houses of Parliament|Westminster]] into perspective".<ref>http://www.totalpolitics.com/blogs/index.php/2010/05/28/diary-of-the-week-matthew-hancock-mp</ref> In June, Hancock was elected to the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], the [[Select committee (Westminster system)|select committee]] responsible for overseeing government expenditures to ensure they are effective and honest.<ref>http://conservativehome.blogs.com/parliament/2010/06/members-of-the-2010-intake-dominate-the-conservative-membership-of-select-committees.html</ref>

==Personal life==
Hancock spent two months in the Arctic, training to heave a 180 pound sled by building up his muscles towing tyres in [[Hyde Park]] at 6am.<ref name="Times"/>  During the trip, together with other participants, he set a world record for the most northerly game of cricket played, with proceeds going to Cancer Research UK. As a result of severe frostbite in the [[Arctic Ocean]], he had to be airlifted out of the Arctic, and still suffers from arthritis in one finger caused by the cold.<ref>[http://www.edp24.co.uk/content/edp24/news/story.aspx?brand=EDPOnline&category=News&tBrand=EDPOnline&tCategory=xDefault&itemid=NOED31%20Jan%202010%2009%3A32%3A41%3A950 Norfolk News, 1 February 2010, accessed 9 May 2010]</ref>

He lives in the constituency in [[Little Thurlow]]<ref name="NJ"/> with his wife Martha and daughter and son.

